Everything you always wanted to know about SPICE pointing offsets *¶

* But were too afraid to ask.

Jupyter notebook https://github.com/gpelouze/spice_pointing_tutorial

Overview¶

  • Global offset:
    • $\approx 70$ arcsec constant offset
    • $\approx 20$ arcsec variation over an orbit
  • Pointing drift: $\lesssim 5$ arcsec over hours, not measured by the AOCS (Attitude and Orbit Control System)
  • Spacecraft jitter: $< 1$ arcsec over minutes, measured by the AOCS

Global pointing offset¶

Offset determination¶

  • Principle: coalign SPICE with EUI FSI (known offset thanks to limb-fitting)
  • Method:
    • convert SPICE rasters into Ly + C III images by summing over , correcting for solar rotation at disk centre
    • determine the offset of the FSI 304 image closest to the middle of the raster (if there is any) using euiprep L1 to L2
    • determine the offset between SPICE and FSI by finding the maximum cross-correlation between the images
  • Yields the offset between the SPICE and Solar Orbiter boresights

Offset monitoring¶

  • Apply to observations since 2021-12-01 (STP-180):
    • SCI_SYNOPTIC_SC_SL04_60.0S_FF (MISO ID 1963) outside of RSW
    • SCI_DYN-DEEP_SC_SL04_19.7S_FF (MISO ID 1975) during RSW
  • Offset changes with solar distance

Temperature dependence¶

  • Offset best correlated to the grating temperature (T_GRAT in the FITS headers)
  • 1st order fit: $\gtrsim 95$ % of values within 1 FWHM of the SPICE PSF

(Relationship to other parameters)¶

Recommendations to update the FITS headers¶

  • Current status: 0th order correction from the cruise phase (W. Thompson):

    • $\Delta X = -83$ [arcsec]
    • $\Delta Y = -68$ [arcsec]

  • Recommended update: 0th / 1st order correction, accurate within 1FWHM of the SPICE PSF:

    • $\Delta X = 0.46$ [arcsec / C] $\times$ T_GRAT [C] $- 85.0$ [arcsec]
    • $\Delta Y = -72.2$ [arcsec]

Update the headers yourself (for now)¶

(This step will likely be obsolete in the future, when the FITS files contain the right offset.)

Remove the 0th cruise-phase offset $(83, 68)$ arcsec, and apply the recommended model:

  • $\Delta X = 0.46$ [arcsec / C] $\times$ T_GRAT [C] $- 85.0$ [arcsec]
  • $\Delta Y = -72.2$ [arcsec]
In [2]:
file = 'data/solo_L2_spice-n-ras_20220325T131648_V01_100663893-000.fits'
with fits.open(file) as hdul:
    h = hdul[0].header
    print('CRVAL1:', h['CRVAL1'], 'arcsec')
    print('CRVAL2:', h['CRVAL2'], 'arcsec')
    h['CRVAL1'] = h['CRVAL1'] - (- 83) + (0.46 * h['T_GRAT'] - 85.0)
    h['CRVAL2'] = h['CRVAL2'] - (- 68) + (- 72.2)
    print('new CRVAL1:', h['CRVAL1'], 'arcsec')
    print('new CRVAL2:', h['CRVAL2'], 'arcsec')

CRVAL1: -79.6110187249 arcsec
CRVAL2: -74.2070821612 arcsec
new CRVAL1: -66.24177472490001 arcsec
new CRVAL2: -78.40708216120001 arcsec

Monitor the global offset yourself¶

(Content warning)

https://github.com/gpelouze/spice_offset_monitoring

Spacecraft jitter → you probably don’t need to correct for this one¶

Small and rapid variations of the spacecraft pointing.

  • Most rasters are unaffected (variation $\lesssim 1$ arcsec)
  • Spacecraft wobbles after wheel offloading (10 to 30 arcsec variations)

Variations are captured by the AOCS (Attitude and Orbit Control System), so they can be corrected if needed.

Correction¶

  • Knowing the pointing offset for each slit position, rasters can be resampled onto a regular grid
  • This mixes $X$ and $t$ for large $X$-offsets, so use it carefully

  • Case A: per-slit offset is in FITS file (WCSDVARR extensions) resample the raster (spice_jitter_correction)
  • Case B: offset is not in the FITS file compute it with the SPICE kernels and resample the raster (spice_stew)

Case A: per-slit offset is in FITS file¶

The per-slit offset is stored in the WCSDVARR extensions. CRDERi and CWERi give the std and maximum variation of the offset within the raster. They should be used to assess whether the correct for the jitter:

In [3]:
file = 'data/solo_L2_spice-n-ras_20210914T025031_V07_67109159-000.fits'
with fits.open(file) as hdul:
    if 'WCSDVARR' in hdul:
        h = hdul[0].header
        print('std X:', h['CRDER1'], 'arcsec')
        print('max X:', h['CWERR1'], 'arcsec')
        print('std Y:', h['CRDER2'], 'arcsec')
        print('max Y:', h['CWERR2'], 'arcsec')

std X: 0.175124208406 arcsec
max X: 1.47314388787 arcsec
std Y: 0.338068853111 arcsec
max Y: 14.1499356645 arcsec

Plot the variations¶

In [4]:
plt.clf()
plt.plot(fits.getdata(file, 'WCSDVARR', 1), label='X')
plt.plot(fits.getdata(file, 'WCSDVARR', 2), label='Y')
plt.legend()
plt.xlabel('Slit position')
plt.ylabel('Relative pointing offset [arcsec]')
plt.show()

Correct the pointing¶

Use spice_jitter_correction to resample the data onto a regular grid. This creates a regularized L2 file (L2r).

In [6]:
import spice_jitter_correction
spice_jitter_correction.correct_jitter(
    'data/solo_L2_spice-n-ras_20210914T025031_V07_67109159-000.fits',
    './data/output_spice_jitter_correction/',
    plot_results=True,
    )

Case 2: offset is not in the FITS file¶

After the pending reprocessing, all files in the archive will contain the offset and this section will be outdated. If you really need to correct for the jitter, wait a few weeks.

Correct the pointing¶

If you really need the pointing now, you can use spice_stew to compute the pointing offset and generate L2r files.

In [8]:
# get the SOLO SPICE kernels (WARNING: clones a 2.9 GiB repository!)
os.environ['SPICE_KERNELS_SOLO'] = './data/spice_kernels/'
!git clone --depth 1 https://repos.cosmos.esa.int/socci/scm/spice_kernels/solar-orbiter.git {os.environ['SPICE_KERNELS_SOLO']}
os.environ['SPICE_KERNELS_SOLO'] += '/kernels'
!sed -i "s+\(^[ ]*PATH_VALUES[ ]*=[ ]* ([ ]*'\)\.\.\('[ ]*)\)$+\1{os.environ['SPICE_KERNELS_SOLO']}\2+" "{os.environ['SPICE_KERNELS_SOLO']}/mk/"*.tm
